ce:section.ce:para:
GQDs were prepared from SWCNTs using a three-step top-down method (Scheme 1
                        ). Firstly, 200mg SWCNTs were refluxed with 100mL 8M HNO3 for 24h. After being cooled to room temperature, the suspension was centrifuged with a centrifugation force of 2770g for 10min to remove the supernatant. The colorless supernatant showed very weak blue fluorescence under 365nm UV light irradiation, suggesting that few GQDs were produced in the procedure. The deposit (O-SWCNTs) was collected after being well washed with deionized (DI) water and centrifugated. The comparison in SEM image between SWCNTs and O-SWCNTs (Fig. 1
                        a, b) shows that the chemical oxidation has no obvious effect on the morphology of the SWCNTs. However, the chemical oxidation can introduce abundant of oxygen-containing groups into the SWCNTs, which is proved by the elemental analysis results and FT-IR spectra (Fig. 2
                        a). The oxygen content of SWCNTs increases obviously from 5.10% to 15.53% (Table 1
                        ). Compared with CC group, the relative IR absorption intensities of CO and C–O groups increase greatly after the refluxing. Moreover, the chemical oxidation can create a lot of disorder structures in SWCNTs, which is revealed by the Raman spectra (Fig. 2b). The intensity ratio (I

                           D
                        /I

                           G
                        ) of the “disorder structure” (D-band) to the “crystalline structure” (G-band) of SWCNTs increases from ∼0.33 to ∼0.82.

Elemental analysis results indicate that both GQDs1 and GQDs2 are composed of primarily carbon and oxygen, and a small amount of hydrogen and nitrogen (Table 1). The XPS results (Fig. 3
                        ) agree well with the elemental analysis results. HRTEM images (Fig. 4
                        ) show that both GQDs1 and GQDs2 are mono-dispersed nanosheets with an average lateral dimension of 8nm. AFM images (Fig. 5
                        ) shows that the topographic heights of both GQDs1 and GQDs2 are mostly less than 0.8nm, with an average height of about 0.5nm, suggesting that both GQDs1 and GQDs2 are mostly single-layered. Both GQDs1 and GQDs2 can be well-dissolved in aqueous solutions (∼20mg/mL in neutral solutions) due to the abundant oxygen-containing groups. Furthermore, both GQDs1 and GQDs2 solutions show robust pH stability (without any noticeable precipitation in the observation of pH 3–12). The high resolution XPS spectra of C1s (Fig. 3) confirm the presence of the functional groups in the two kinds of GQDs: the sp2 CC (284.2eV), sp3 C–C (285.0eV), C–O (286.0eV), CO (288.1eV), and CC–O (288.8eV). As also shown in Fig. 6
                        , both GQDs1 and GQDs2 display the stretching vibrations of O–H (3480cm−1), CO (1740cm−1), CC (1620cm−1), C–H (1390cm−1), C–O (1240cm−1). From the comparison of the two FTIR spectra, it can be known that the relative IR absorption intensities of C–O and CO peaks of GQDs2 are much stronger than those of GQDs1, suggesting that GQDs2 should have higher oxidation degree than GQDs1.Although both aqueous solutions of GQDs1 and GQDs2 are yellow under white light, they are different in UV–vis absorption spectra (Fig. 7
                        ). The solution of GQDs1 shows a broad UV–vis absorption below 600nm, with an obvious shoulder peak centered around 350nm. The solution of GQDs2 also shows a broad UV–vis absorption below 600nm with a peak. However, the shoulder absorption peak of GQDs2 is obviously red-shifted and centered around 460nm. Besides the different UV–vis absorption behaviors, GQDs1 and GQDs2 also exhibit different photoluminescence (PL) properties. The solution of GQDs1 emits green luminescence under excitation of a beam of 365nm UV light, whereas the solution of GQDs2 exhibits yellow luminescence. The emission spectra of the two GQD solutions show different excitation-dependences. With the increase in excitation wavelength gradually from 300nm to 560nm, the maximum emission wavelength of GQDs1 is red-shifted accordingly. In contrast, GQDs2 keeps stable at 515nm until the excitation wavelength is longer than 460nm. Although the exact PL mechanisms of these GQDs are still unclear, more and more researchers tend to believe that the PL of carbon-based luminescent materials is attributed to their surface states, which may be affected by the functional groups [21–24]. It has been reported that the surface oxidation degree can affect the PL property of carbon-based luminescent materials, namely the PL wavelength increases with the oxidation degree [21–24]. As mentioned above, GQDs1 and GQDs2 have been revealed to be similar in morphology, while GQDs2 have a higher oxidation degree than GQDs1. Therefore, it is reasonable to conclude that the difference in optical properties between GQDs1 and GQDs2 should be caused by their difference in degree of oxidation.
